{"title_page": "David Karp (pomologist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = yellow\n| name          = David Karp\n| image         = David Karp at CVC.jpg\n| caption       = '''David Karp'''<br />in front of an [[orange (fruit)|orange tree]] <br /> at the<br /> [[University of California, Riverside Citrus Variety Collection|'''\"Citrus Variety Collection\"'''<br /> of the<br />'''University of California, Riverside]]'''.\n| birth_name     = David Karp\n| birth_date     = 1958\n| birth_place    = [[Los Angeles]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = Pomologist, writer\n| training     = Graduated from [[Wesleyan University]], [[Middletown, Connecticut]], in 1979 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[Medieval art|Late Antique Studies]], [[Magna Cum Laude]], [[Phi Beta Kappa]].\n| title         = Department of Botany and Plant Sciences, at the [[University of California, Riverside]].\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''David Karp''' (born 1958) is an active [[pomologist]], traveler and writer,<ref name=\"Seabrook\">{{Citation\n |last=Seabrook \n |first=John \n |title=Our Far-Flung Correspondents, The Fruit Detective \n |newspaper=The New Yorker \n |date=August 19, 2002 \n |url=http://www.booknoise.net/johnseabrook/stories/culture/detective/index.html \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703012800/http://www.booknoise.net/johnseabrook/stories/culture/detective/index.html \n |archivedate=2010-07-03 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"Seed Savers\">{{cite book |title= Member Profile: David Karp; International Fruit Hunter; [[Seed Savers Exchange]] Magazine |last= Torgrimson |first= John|authorlink= |coauthors= |date= Summer 2010|publisher= |location= |isbn= |page= |pages= 12\u201314|url= |accessdate=}}</ref> who calls himself a ''Fruit detective''.<ref name=\"Smithsonian\">{{Citation\n  | last = Crawford\n  | first = Amy\n  | title = An Interview with Author David Karp, Fruit Detective\n  | newspaper = Smithsonian.com\n  | pages = 1\u20132\n  | date = July 1, 2006\n  | url = http://www.smithsonianmag.com/people-places/karp.html\n  | access-date = March 5, 2009\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090514040514/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/people-places/karp.html\n  | archive-date = May 14, 2009\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nDavid is the son of Harvey Karp, a businessman, whose [[East Hampton (village), New York|East Hampton]] home was reputed to be a palace.<ref name=\"Seabrook\" /> He was fluent in [[Latin]] when he graduated from high school. At 20, while majoring in [[medieval art]] studies at [[Wesleyan University]], he published a translation of the 6th-century Latin author [[Venantius Fortunatus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.willamette.edu/cla/classics/careers/karp/|title=Classics: David Karp \u2013 Willamette University|work=willamette.edu}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, he started a career in risk arbitrage and option trading on [[Wall Street]], has worked for  gourmet specialty store ''Citarella'' and acted as a provisioner for [[Dean & DeLuca]]. Recovering from a serious drug addiction, he changed course and began a new career as a freelance fruit writer.<ref name=\"Seabrook\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.willamette.edu/cla/classics/VIPs/karp.html |title=Willametta Classical Studies |access-date=2010-08-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707231546/http://www.willamette.edu/cla/classics/VIPs/karp.html |archive-date=2007-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKarp moved to California in 1999.<ref name=\"Seabrook\" />\n\n== Writings ==\nKarp's photographs and writings appear in his weekly column, Market Watch, at the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', and he has written articles for ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Gourmet (magazine)|Gourmet]]'', ''[[Smithsonian (magazine)|Smithsonian]]'', ''[[Sunset (magazine)|Sunset]]'', ''[[Star-Ledger]]''  and ''[[Saveur]]'' publications.<ref name=\"Seed Savers\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://splendidtable.publicradio.org/souptonuts/farmstand.html |title=The Splendid Table |access-date=2010-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705024251/http://splendidtable.publicradio.org/souptonuts/farmstand.html |archive-date=2010-07-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He has been a guest on the Saturday morning food show on radio station [[KCRW]].<ref name=\" KCRW\">{{Citation\n  | last = Schnabel\n  | first = Tom\n  | author-link =\n  | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = David Karp\n  | newspaper = KCRW\n  | pages =\n  | year =\n  | date = Aug 5, 2009\n  | url = http://www.kcrw.com/music/programs/gd/gd090805david_karp}}</ref>\n\nWhen the threat of [[Huanglongbing|citrus greening]] first appeared in the U.S., Karp wrote in the ''New York Times'' to alert the public of the disease's risks.<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/26/science/26citrus.html?_r=1&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Deadly Pathogen Harms Florida Citrus Groves]\"</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\n\n=== Citrus Documentation at CVC ===\nKarp is an associate in the [[University of California Citrus Experiment Station|Agricultural Experiment Station at the University of California, Riverside]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://festivaloffruit.org/David_Karp.html |title=David Karp |work=festivaloffruit.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310101630/http://www.festivaloffruit.org/David_Karp.html |archivedate=2010-03-10 }}</ref> working to photograph and document the more than 1,000 varieties grown at the [[University of California, Riverside Citrus Variety Collection|Citrus Variety Collection of the University of California]]. Displayed on the CVC website], these photos are accessible to researchers throughout the world.\n\n=== Citrus germplasm in China ===\nHe helped co-found the Chinese Citrus Germplasm Repository in [[Jiangshui]] (about 50 miles from [[Kunming]]), province of [[Yunnan]].<ref name=\"Seed Savers\" />\n\n=== Bunyard Orchard ===\nDavid Karp and Andy Mariani are co-founders of the Bunyard Orchard of [[heirloom]] [[stone fruit]] in [[Morgan Hill, California]].<ref name=\"Caliber\">{{cite web|url=http://gcfs.ucpress.edu/content/9/3/v|title=Contributors - Gastronomica: The Journal of Critical Food Studies|work=ucpress.edu}}</ref>\n\n=== Unforbidden Fruit ===\nKarp became involved as a researcher in a joint project between the [[University of California, Riverside]] and the [[USDA]] to prevent smuggling of fruit into California that may harbor insects that could threaten the state\u2019s fruit industry. The project \u2014Unforbidden Fruits: Preventing Citrus Smuggling by Introducing Varieties Culturally Significant to Ethnic Communities\u2014focuses on making disease-free [[germplasm]] of citrus and non-citrus fruit available to Californian nurseries and tree farmers, to replace the illicit demand.<ref name=\"Seed Savers\" />\n[[File:Tejocotes2.jpg|thumb|[[Tejocote]]]]\nA non-citrus fruit that the project has targeted is ''\"[[tejocote]]\"'' (''[[Crataegus mexicana]]'', sometimes called ''Crataegus pubescens''), a fruit that is grown in the highlands of [[Mexico]]. Because it was not being grown in the U.S., it was often smuggled into the country and sold to Mexicans who wanted to use it to serve the traditional fruit drink called ''[[ponche]]'' at Christmastime. Now that ''tejocote'' is being grown legally in California, much of the smuggling into the country has dropped off.<ref name=\"Seed Savers\" />\n\n=== RosBREED ===\nKarp is a member of the \"extension advisory panel\" for RosBREED, an organization dedicated to improving [[rosaceae]] crops through marker assisted crossbreeding.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rosbreed.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/RosBREED-I-Informational-Handout.pdf |title=RossBREED |access-date=2010-08-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707124725/http://rosbreed.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/RosBREED-I-Informational-Handout.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Fruits of interest ==\n[[File:Mangosteen3.jpg|Mangosteen|thumb]]\n\n=== Mangosteen ===\nKarp has written several articles on the availability of the [[mangosteen]] in the United States, due to fears they harbor the Asian [[Tephritidae|fruit fly]]. He wrote articles in the ''New York Times'' announcing the renewed U.S. law on July 23, 2007, when [[irradiation|irradiated]] imports from [[Thailand]] were allowed upon [[USDA]] approval,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/27/dining/27frui.html | work=The New York Times | title=Welcome at the Border: Thai Fruits, Once Banned | first=David | last=Karp | date=June 27, 2007 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/09/dining/09mang.html?ex=1312776000&en=0d1a76f2087e406d&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss. | work=The New York Times | title=Forbidden? Not the Mangosteen | first=David | last=Karp | date=August 9, 2006 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> and one following its trade at the local markets.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/08/dining/08mang.html | work=The New York Times | title=Mangosteens Arrive, but Be Prepared to Pay | first=David | last=Karp | date=August 8, 2007 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Greengage plum ===\nDavid believes the [[greengage plum]] is the most delicious fruit on the world,<ref name=\"Smithsonian\" /> and traveled to [[Moissac]], France (its primary center of cultivation), to investigate it.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Karp\n  | first = David\n  | author-link =\n  | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = A Finicky Fruit Is Sweet When Coddled\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | pages =\n  | year =\n  | date = September 1, 2004\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/09/01/dining/01GREE.html?pagewanted=print&position=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em