url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613034138/http://www.gourmet.com/magazine/2000s/2000/09/USAgrown \n |archivedate=2011-06-13 \n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karp, David}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pomologists]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = yellow\n| name          = David Karp\n| image         = David Karp at CVC.jpg\n| caption       = '''David Karp'''<br />in front of an [[orange (fruit)|orange tree]] <br /> at the<br /> [[University of California, Riverside Citrus Variety Collection|'''\"Citrus Variety Collection\"'''<br /> of the<br />'''University of California, Riverside]]'''.\n| birth_name     = David Karp\n| birth_date     = 1958\n| birth_place    = [[Los Angeles]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = Pomologist, writer\n| training     = Graduated from [[Wesleyan University]], [[Middletown, Connecticut]], in 1979 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[Medieval art|Late Antique Studies]], [[Magna Cum Laude]], [[Phi Beta Kappa]].\n| title         = Department of Botany and Plant Sciences, at the [[University of California, Riverside]].\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''David Karp''' (born 1958) is an active [[pomologist]], traveler and writer,<ref name=\"Seabrook\">{{Citation\n |last=Seabrook \n |first=John \n |title=Our Far-Flung Correspondents, The Fruit Detective \n |newspaper=The New Yorker \n |date=August 19, 2002 \n |url=http://www.booknoise.net/johnseabrook/stories/culture/detective/index.html \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703012800/http://www.booknoise.net/johnseabrook/stories/culture/detective/index.html \n |archivedate=2010-07-03 \n}}</ref><ref name=\"Seed Savers\">{{cite book |title= Member Profile: David Karp; Int